observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct all department heads and designated supply officers to (a) formulate policies and procedures in the control and monitoring of all inventories purchased and received; 
(b) religiously conduct physical count of all inventories in order to establish the correct balances of the inventory accounts; 
(c) ensure the preparation and timely submission of reports pertaining to the issuance of inventory items; and 
(d) strictly comply with the rules and regulations contained in the NGAS Manual for LGUs for the proper recording, valuation and preparation of the required inventory reports. 

Also, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to instruct the staff preparing JEVs to properly analyze each transaction before recording in the books to ensure that the JEV prepared reflects the correct accounting entries in the recording of transactions.

We recommended that the Municipal Accounting Office (a) exert best efforts to determine the composition of the unidentified balances recorded in the Due to NGAs accounts (GF and TF); 
(b) draw the appropriate entry to derecognize the liability to DSWD amounting to the ₱645,877.00 representing return of grants of SLP members, this amount should be transferred to the SLP Association/s; and 
(c) make the adjusting entry to correct the transfer of fund from GF to TF amounting to ₱7,920,000.00.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant instruct the personnel in charge of recording the transactions to; 
(a) draw the appropriate journal entries to correct the accounting errors committed; and 
(b) ensure compliance with the provisions of the NGAS Manual for LGUs for the proper recording of transactions.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant 
(a) record and adjust immediately all reconciling items found in the respective books, and henceforth, conduct quarterly reconciliation of balances pursuant to Section 181 of GAAM, Volume I so that errors committed by either the Municipal Treasurer or Municipal Accounting Office may be appropriately adjusted or posted; 
(b) prepare bank reconciliation statements for the latest bank statement received covering all depository accounts; 
(c) maintain a separate ledger and cashbook for the HDMF e-gov bank account to produce accurate accounting records and financial statements; and (d) call the attention of the concerned Barangays Treasurers for the turn-over of the CTC booklets issued to them, and henceforth, closely monitor all accountable forms issued to Barangays.

We recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) strictly observe the provisions of RA No. 9184 particularly the 
(a) posting of ITB, COA, Contract/PO and NTP; 
(b) invitation of observers in all stages of the procurement process; 
(c) preparation and submission of the PERT/CPM network; and 
(d) submission of DOLE Approved Construction Safety and Health Program of bidders/contractors.

We also recommended that Management submit a written explanation on the non-provision of the contractor of complete personal protective equipment of laborers during the project duration despite inclusion thereof in the total contract cost.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, through the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board:
issue a revised Executive Order for the inclusion of the representatives from the fields and industries required under Section 12 of Republic Act No. 9003, to wit: (i) manufacturing or packaging industry; and (ii) concerned government agency possessing relevant technical and marketing expertise;
provide additional manpower to the MENRO to ensure the regular monitoring of the implementation of SWM-related projects and ordinances and to aid in the strict imposition of fines and penalties against violators of prohibited acts;
devise mechanisms that will reduce the volume of garbage and waste materials being turned-over to Metro Clark Waste Management Corporation (MCWC) to decrease the amount of tipping fees being paid by the Municipality;
allot sufficient budget for the implementation of the following SWM PPAs: (1) products, facilities, technologies and processes to enhance proper solid waste management; (2) research programs; (3) technical assistance; and (4) capability building activities in order to raise awareness and increase the compliance rate of households and other concerned constituents; and
improve its compliance with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9003 or the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000.

observations.managementAction:
The MENRO Head agreed on the recommendations and offered the following comments:


On the inclusion of representatives from the (i) manufacturing or packaging industry; and (ii) concerned government agency possessing relevant technical and marketing expertise, the matter will be discussed in the coming meetings of the MSWMB;
Continuous efforts on information education campaign to barangays, schools, and house were being done by the MENRO staff. The garbage collectors were already instructed to not collect unsegregated garbage. Since HOLCIM will start receiving plastic materials this 2019, the plastic materials will be delivered to them so as to decrease the volume of waste materials being turned-over to MCWC which will eventually decrease the amount of tipping fees being paid to the latter.

