observations.managementAction:
The Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer offered the following comments:
The Ᵽ1000,000.00 appropriation for CY 2017 as reported by the Budget Office was focused only on the expenditures of the CAPIN. Other programs related to RA 9344 were not reported. For CY 2017, the total budget for the protection of children is Ᵽ4,877,000.00 which includes the aid for ECCD Service Providers/Day Care Workers;
The MSWD Office is presently on its process of establishing data base for all sectors (women, youth, solo parents, Day Care Children, Senior Citizens, 4Ps, vulnerable and indigent). For the children sectors, the complete data for day care children were on hand. While, the data for the youth sectors were incomplete, thus we have not included it in the report;
They are in the process of completing the Local State of Children Report; and
The MSWD Office has designated a focal person to focus on the LCPC concern so that the objective of the organization will be implemented effectively.

Meanwhile, on the low-impact projects implemented, according to the MSWDO official in-charge of CAPIN, her office proposed some project and activities but these were not implemented in 2017. On the other hand, she clarified that some of the charges in the LCPC budget were not initiated by the CAPIN. She also added that the responsibility for the implementation of the projects was not clearly vested in her office.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, henceforth,
require the Municipal officials and employees to observe prudence in government spending by authorizing those to attend seminars and trainings that are only related and beneficial to their duties and functions and may contribute to professional development and attainment of the Municipal’s goals and objectives; 
install internal controls governing travel and attendance to training programs giving emphasis that the venue of seminars and training programs be limited to areas within the immediate jurisdiction of the LGU, instead of island regions like Palawan, Davao, Cebu, Iloilo, Cagayan de Oro, General Santos City, Bacolod, Camarines Sur, and the like; 
require the Municipal Accountant to check the adequacy of  supporting documents such as but not limited to the following: (i) letter of invitation of host/ sponsoring agency/ organization addressed to the agency participants;  (ii) travel orders which shall indicate the purpose of travel and the urgency and necessity of the travel; (iii) certification from the Head of the Agency as to the absolute necessity of the expenses together with the corresponding bills or receipts, if the expenses incurred for official travel exceeded the prescribed rate per day; (iv) quotations of three travel agencies if the seminar would require traveling by airplane; (v) paper/electronic plane ticket, boarding pass and terminal fee; (vi) itinerary receipt from the airline company/travel agency; and (vii) the report on the seminar attended and recommendations, if any;
require the concerned Municipal Officials and employees, especially those who attended seminars and conventions who are not members of the organizations initiating the seminar or who may not have interest in the seminar topic, to submit an acceptable explanation as to the absolute necessity of the travels for evaluation of the Audit Team, otherwise the amount of travel expenses claimed shall be refunded pursuant to National Budget Circular (NBC) No. 563 dated April 22, 2016 and Executive Order No. 298.

We recommended that the Municipal Engineer 
ensure that detailed engineering is performed, including the preparation of plans and specifications and program of work containing the material requirements and work description of items prior to the implementation of the infrastructure project; 
conduct site inspection prior to the preparation of program of work and plans and specifications and field monitoring on the progress and development of the projects to ensure compliance with the required technical specifications; 
require the Contractor to cause the repair of the portion of the project found defective at no additional cost to the Municipality; 
check Contractor’s compliance with quality control policies and minimum tests requirements as to quality of materials and mixtures to avoid the occurrence of structural defects and deficiencies within the life expectancy of infrastructure projects; and
henceforth, observe the provisions of RA No. 9184 on the implementation of projects requiring the preparation of variation orders.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) require the Municipal Engineer and the Accountant to submit the noted insufficiencies in documentation as enumerated above; 

(b)  submit a written explanation on the failure to implement the Supplementary Project as agreed upon in the MOA signed by the Municipality and the ECCDC; 


(c) submit the operational guidelines of the NCDC in accordance with the promulgation by the ECCD Council; and 

(d) require the concerned Municipal official to work on the appraisal and titling of the donated lot to the Municipality to facilitate the recording in the books.

