We recommended that the 

(a) Municipal Planning Development Officer (MPDO), and other key officials involved in the preparation of the budget  prepare an AIP based on the Municipality’s CDP to ensure that the desired development objective is gradually attained; 
(b) MPDO ensure that the aid to barangays for their priority development projects are aligned to the development target of the Municipality as contained in the CDP;
(c) Municipal Engineer work on the completion of the supporting documents to preclude the noted transactions from being suspended or disallowed in audit; and 

(d) Municipal Accountant to ensure that documents are sufficient before payment to the contractor/supplier is made.

We recommended that the: 

a) MDRRMO  appropriately draft, submit and update the LDRRMP and LDRRMFIP;

b) Municipal Accountant 

(i) submit monthly reports on the sources and utilization of DRRMF based on the required format of COA Circular 2012-002; 

(ii) facilitate the immediate transfer of the remaining balance of the 5% DRMMF to the special trust fund account; and 

(iii)  ensure the submission of complete supporting documents on all claims before certifying the completeness thereof;

(c) Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO) ensure the revision of the Annual Investment Program for the inclusion of new expenditure items which will be charged against the unexpended balance of the 5% DRRMF; and

d) Municipal officials concerned comply with the provisions of Republic Act No. 10121, DPWH Department Order No. 22, Series of 2015 and relevant COA issued circulars and memoranda.

We recommended that management:

(a)	reconstitute and strengthen the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) based on the provisions of Republic Act No. 9710; 

(b)	issue an Executive Order or Administrative Order for the revision and update of the GAD Executive Committee (ExeCom) and Technical Working Group (TWG) members;

(c)	encourage and direct the GFPS Committee and Technical Working Group to perform its mandated tasks and to strengthen the monitoring and evaluation system to assess the effectiveness and efficiency of their gender mainstreaming efforts;

(d)	where feasible, the agency may also establish a GAD Office or unit under the Office of the LCE that will support and coordinate all GAD-related PPAs and concerns of the LGU GFPS. The LCE may also appoint or designate the LGU personnel to manage the GAD office and/or unit.

(e)	exert  efforts to come up with a database on sex-disaggregated data or perform gender analysis to ensure that allocation of funds on GAD-related PPAs to ensure is not based on incorrect assumption and stereotypes; 

(f)	submit the required GAD Accomplishment report for further evaluation; and

(g)	ensure that the allocated funds are maximized for the implementation of the GAD activities.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

(a) install an effective control and monitoring mechanism on the receipt, recording, storage/management, and distribution of the procured and donated relief goods establishing the persons responsible in the discharge of specific undertaking;


(b) require the MSWD Officer to submit the:

(i) distribution report and Issuance Form for in-kind donations or its equivalent; 

(ii) monthly report of receipt and issuances of acquired and donated relief goods; 

(iii) inventory report of acquired and donated relief goods as of date; and 

(iv) copy of the RIS issued by the PAGCOR for the donated FFP; 

(c) require the LDRRM Officer to submit the distribution report or its equivalent for the procured goods which include the blankets, mats, camping tents, and folding beds; 

(d) require the authorized official to issue an Acknowledgement Receipt for all donated relief goods and equipment accepted in behalf of the LCE to be posted in the Registry of Donated Relief Goods by the Supply Officer;


(e) require the Municipal Accountant to adjust in the books the recording of relief goods to the appropriate inventory account;

(f) require the Procurement Officer to request for a replacement order to the Supplier for delivering about to expire products at the time of delivery or hold the Supply Officer liable for receiving the products without considering their expiration dates;

(g) improve and expand the storage for relief goods by considering its absorptive capacity and warehousing condition to avoid the spoilage and physical quality deterioration of relief goods;  and

(h) strictly abide by the accounting and reporting guidelines on the receipt, management, and distribution of procured and donated relief goods.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Management:

(a) require the Bids and Awards Committee to 

(i) procure common-use supplies directly from the PS to ensure economy and savings; 

(ii) stop the practice of splitting purchases, instead consolidate all material requirements good for a maximum of three-month consumption and employ competitive bidding; 

(iii) refrain from acquiring common-use supplies from suppliers unable to prove/confirm their financial, technical and legal capability and those acting only as agent/middleman for the LGU; and 

(iv) post in the PhilGEPS the RFQ and Award of the procurements covered by small value procurements of more than P50,000.00 for seven (7) calendar days, except for unforeseen contingency requiring immediate purchase, for information purposes;


(b) require the Property Officer and the Municipal Accountant to install an effective control mechanism to ensure that the supplies and materials in the custody of the LGU units are existing, monitored and controlled; and

(c) require the Municipal Accountant to refrain from recognizing in the books the purchases of supplies and materials directly to expense accounts but instead use the appropriate inventory account in accordance with the existing accounting rules and regulations, to ensure accountability.

We reiterated our recommendations that the SB enact a revenue ordinance authorizing the collection of rental fee for the use of farms tractors and other farm equipment setting the rules and regulations including the fixing of the amount to be collected pursuant to Section 129 RA No. 7160.

We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

(a) require the MAO to 

(i) draft a set of procedural guidelines and documentation on the utilization of the equipment in consultation with the Local Finance Committee; 

(ii) discontinue the receipt of collections from rental/lease of wheeled tractors by unauthorized collectors, but direct all lessors to pay at the Municipal Treasurer’s Office for appropriate issuance of official receipt and recording in the books of accounts; 

(iii) turn over the collections from the use of farm tractors for 2016, including the computed collections for the period October 24, 2016 to December 29, 2016 totaling ₱942,880.00 to the Municipal Treasurer for issuance of official receipt; 

(iv) submit the logbook on the whereabouts of all the farm tractors as well as the list of the users/farmers, number of hectares plowed, and amount paid from January 21, 2014 to date to determine the amount actually collected for the use of tractors; and

(b) require the Municipal Treasurer to re-assess the actual cash collections in the custody of the MAO as of date for proper turn-over and appropriate reporting of collections.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

(a) require the Municipal Health Officer (MHO) and the RHU heads to 

(i) submit a written explanation on the basis or derivation of the approved budget for the contract (ABC); 

(ii) consider the use of the Philippine Drug Price Reference Index (DPRI) to serve as a guide in the efficient and sourcing of pharmaceutical products; 

(iii) purchase medicines that are within the Philippine National Drug Formulary (PNDF); and 


(iv) maintain and submit the following:

	stocks inventory report showing the quantity of medicines received from the Municipality, the complete description of medicines received, the quantity of medicines utilized within a month, and balance of medicines in quantity per item at the end of the month; 

	utilization report which shows the complete name of patient, date of visit, complete address, age, gender, health complaints of patient, diagnosis, complete description and quantity of dispensed medicines;

	monthly summary of medicines utilized which shows the quantity of medicines dispensed to patients taken from utilization report and complete description of medicines;

	annual inventory report which shows the quantity of medicines remained in stocks as of year-end and complete description  per items of medicines; and

	stock cards for drugs and medicines, and medical supplies using the format prescribed in the NGAS Manual for LGUs; 

(b) require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to  submit in writing  explanation for the 

(i) inaction on the observed unreasonable percentage increase in the price of the medicines; 

(ii) noted deficiencies, irregularities and inconsistencies on the submitted technical bidding documents of Steritex Medical System, warranty security, and the award of contract to a lone bidder despite the presence of other suppliers in the opening of bids; and

(c) henceforth, 

(i) require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the required documentary requirements supporting all purchases especially for medicines are present; and 

(ii) require the BAC to strictly comply with the Revised IRR of RA 9184, COA Circulars, PD 1445 and other related government issued circulars and memoranda.

We recommended that the:

(a) BAC and all Consignment Committees 

(i) strictly observe and comply with the specific guidelines and procedures in the procurement of consigned drugs and medicines prescribed under the Municipal Ordinance No. 001-2015 and DOH Administrative Order Nos. 145 series of 2004 and 2006-0039 dated December 8, 2006; and 

(ii) and monitor all activities under the consignment system to adhere to the principle of transparency, accountability, equity, efficiency and economy in its consignment process;

(b) MCH Accountant 

(i) prepare the Monthly Utilization Report of Consigned Drugs and Medicines and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording in the books; 


(ii) make use of the prescribed forms such as Consignment Request and Stocks Delivery Slip which shall be duly approved; 

(iii) ensure that Consignment Orders are duly signed by the Head of the Consignee and acknowledged/received by the Consignor; and 

(iv) ensure prompt payment to Consignors to avoid the recurrence of cases of stock-outs for drugs, medicines, and medical supplies in the Pharmacy Section and Central Supply Room of the Mexico Community Hospital partly due to delayed payment to the Suppliers; and

(c) Supply Officer submit to the Auditor’s Office the perfected Consignment Contract/Agreement for review of the consignment arrangement with the consignors and to allow the walkthrough test of pertinent transactions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

(a)	through the MSWDO, request for the clear-cut criteria and eligibility standards in the selection of the beneficiaries for seed-capital assistance prior to implementation of the project to avoid confusion in the selection process of beneficiaries. Consideration should be given to those individuals belonging to the grass-roots level of society, with proper guidance, to help them uplift their living conditions; 

(b)	require the MSWDO to transfer to the Municipal AGDB under the Trust Fund all the seed-capital collections deposited in a private bank;

(c)	require the Municipal Treasurer and the Accountant to issue official receipt and account/record in the books the appropriate entry from the grant to the collection of seed-capital assistance, respectively;

(d)	submit the program of activities covered in the trainings to support the payments of honoraria and henceforth, ensure that corresponding taxes are withheld pursuant to BIR revenue regulations;

(e)	provide a space for the tools and equipment purchased for various livelihood trainings and funded under the BUB program to maximize their useful life;

(f)	exercise prudence in the use of government funds by ensuring that the contracted prices for meals and snacks provided to trainees are advantageous to the government and limit the meals and snacks to legitimate participants in the trainings;

(g)	require the Municipal Treasurer and the MSWDO to submit a written explanation on the delayed delivery/purchase of  training materials costing ₱20,000.00;

(h)	require the MSWDO to prepare and submit an evaluation report for each trainings conducted indicating their success indicators for validation purposes; and 

henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 by providing sufficient advertisement on projects to be undertaken prior to their implementation to ensure that all individuals most especially those belonging to the grass-roots level are given opportunity to be beneficiaries of the free trainings and capital assistance provided by the government.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:

(a) Municipal Agriculturist to 

(i) work on the completion of the supporting documents before payment to the supplier is made; 

(ii) submit a workable project proposal and breeding design program; 

(c) ensure that target beneficiaries are carefully considered prior to the implementation of the project;

(b) Bids and Awards Committee and its Secretariat, in coordination with the requesting Office/Department, to ensure that vital issues or any impediments towards an efficient project implementation must be finalized and resolved prior to conducting bidding activities;

(c) Bids and Awards Committee members and the personnel/officials of the Municipal Agriculture Office to submit an explanation and/or justification on the pricing of the  carabaos; and

(d)	Municipal Accountant to compute and deduct the amount of liquidated damages for the delay in the delivery of the ten Caraheifers from the amount payable to the VPowerAgro Trading.
